column168: July 1, 2022, a metal tote of hazardous, UN1219, Isopropyl Alcohol, 3, PG II had a small pinhole in the bottom of the metal tote causing a release. A very minimal release occurred and was contained by absorbent pads. A contractor responded to the incident to transfer the product from the damaged tote into a new 330-gallon poly tote pending disposition.

The van trailer in which this drum was loaded was picked up from Solvay Augusta on Tues. 7/5/22. The drum was not leaking at this time. The driver overnighted at a location and pre-tripped his truck and trailer the next day, Wed. 7/6/22. The drum was still secure. When the driver arrived at the Clean Harbors Environmental Services transportation Hub in Stone Mountain, GA., the trailer was being unloaded and the release was discovered. The point and cause of the release was found to be two small pin holes located approx. 1" from the bottom chime, apparently resulting from exterior corrosion. There was no evidence of the drum being punctured in-transit The released material was remediated by in-house technicians with proper HazMat Emergency Response training. The affected drum was over-packed, along with the contaminated remediation materials.
column169: The generator, Solvay Augusta, has previous history of offering defective drums for transport. This will be addressed with the generator by the account manager assigned to this customer. The branch that routinely picks up waste from this generator will be remedially trained regarding proper and thorough container inspection. Had this drum been properly inspected prior to being accepted, the corroded area where the pin holes manifested could have been identified and the drum could have been over-packed prior to transport thereby avoiding this release.

On 6/20/2022, the covered hopper railcar was loaded in Cheyenne, WY with 220,100 lbs. of ammonium nitrate fertilizer (AN). The railcar departed Cheyenne on 6/21/2022 and was delivered to industry at Tooele, UT site on 6/28/2022. The railcar was transported by the Union Pacific Railroad (UP) from Cheyenne, WY to Tooele, UT and made five stops for transfer to other trains over the eight-day journey. The car remained at the Rocky Mountain Rail Repair rail siting until 7/6//2022, when it was moved to the Savage Services transloading site for offloading. Savage Services noted that all seals were present with the exception of the one for the center bottom gate.  The Savage employees noted a steel cable was clipped to the hasp instead of a seal. Savage employees did not inspect further and began offloading the AN.  The Savage employees subsequently discovered the railcar was missing 40,581 lbs. of AN and notified Dyno Nobel.    Dyno Nobel notified FRA inspector Jerome Sedillo who advised to notify the NRC.  Dyno Nobel notified the Savage Services Ops Manager that he needed to report the incident to the NRC since he was in possession of the railcar and its material.  Dyno Nobel contacted the UP and advised them of the incident to inspect their railyards and tracks for evidence of AN.  On 7/7/2022, Dyno Nobel was informed that Savage Services did not make the report, so Dyno Nobel contacted the NRC.     Savage, Rocky Mountain, and the UP did not locate evidence of AN in their railyards or along the tracks.  The Cheyenne loading site also inspected their site and did not find evidence of AN on the tracks.  On 7/10/2022, Rocky Mountain inspected the railcar and found the center gravity gate had a worn-out drive bar, and the pinion was not engaging the door rack.  The inspector stated this will allow the door to move easily and would not permit it to completely close when loaded.  During transit, it appears the bottom gate opened and spilled AN, which dispersed along the route within the railroad tracks.  It also appears someone may have discovered it and attempted to secure the gate using the steel cable, but no one reported it.  In the event the UP locates AN prill along the rail line or in any of the UP yards, Dyno Nobel will coordinate with them to recover and clean up the prill by hiring a hazardous materials contractor.   Dyno Nobel inspected their loading site, interviewed the railcar loaders and track crew, and reviewed the loading procedures with those employees.   See attached documents for the detailed timeline of the incident, the railcar inspection report, and the shipping papers. column168: FORKLIFT DAMAGE

On 7/8/2022 Veolia employees from the West Virginia office picked up a load of containers from a customers site. The majority of the shipment was 55 gallon drums of flammable paint. The drums were loaded 4 to a pallet and were then loaded onto Veolia's truck with no issue. Upon return to Veolia's West Virginia officer the Veolia driver attempted to offload the box truck using a seated forklift. As he was driving over the dock plate that leads into the warehouse one of the drums that was loaded on the pallet he was carrying tilted forward and fell off the pallet. The drum fell to the floor of the truck and the lid popped up when it hit the ground leading to the release of white paint. The paint was contained inside the truck using spill dry and absorbent pads. Following the incident Veolia employees inspected both the pallet and the 55 gallon drum. It was discovered that the pallet was missing several boards which made it unstable. When then employee drove over the dock plate the bump and incline allowed the drum to tip into the gap left from the broken pallet and fall forward to the ground. When the drum hit the ground the lid folded up allowing the liquid to leak from the container. The time of the release was less than a minute. Our employee was able to quickly pick up the container to prevent further leakage after the event occurred. All spill debris was properly cleaned up and placed inside a spill clean up drum for proper disposal.
column169: Veolia's EHS Manager we will be meeting with the West Virginia team on 7/15/2022 to discuss this incident. The focus of that conversation will center around checking pallets and containers before taking possession of the container at the customer's site. Veolia should never accept a container or a pallet that is in poor condition. We will also discuss the importance slowing down and taking extra caution when driving over a dock plate. When driving over a dock plate employees need to understand that they will be backing over a bump and that bump will also put them at a slight downward incline. This presents an perfect opportunity for a drum to tip or slide so they need to account for that while they are driving into the warehouse.

column168: On 7/13/22 a leaking drum was identiffied on Veolia's truck that was parked at Veolia's ten day intransit facility in College Park, GA.  Further investigation revealed that the spill was caused from a pinhole leak in the drum located where a metal plate with the UN information was welded to the drum. There was less than 1 gallon of liquid was released. All of the liquid that was released was contained inside of the truck.  When the release was first identified, the Velia Operations Manager was notified the team conducted a full investigation to perform remediation of the spill. The team put pads underneath the truck to make sure that nothing would get on the ground. Fortunately, no waste spilled out of the truck. The team cleaned up the spill with sodium bicarbonate and overpacked the leaking drum. The truck was then decontaminated further with sodium bicarbonate. The total time of the spill cleanup took approximately 3 hours. The 4 other drums of this waste did not leak.
column169: Veolia is retuning all 5 drums back to the shipper for repacking into stainless steel drums that do not have UN specification plates welded to the container.

column168: While at the shipper on 07/13/2022, the driver was told when she inquired that the freight was not hazmat. The driver was not allowed on the dock during loading and when she went in the cargo box to secure the freight there were no hazmat markings or labels visible.   When the freight delivered on 07/14/2022, the driver was on the dock area while the freight was offloaded and saw that there were hazmat markings and labels on the freight. She further noticed that all remaining freight in the cargo box was loaded so that the side with the hazmat markings and labels loaded to be facing the sidewalls of the cargo box which would prevent her from seeing the hazmat details. She took photos of the freight and those were escalated to me in the Safety department.  The shipment was booked as non-hazardous, so I contacted the shipper to see if there was some special exemption that allowed the freight to move without shipping paperwork since I did not see any that applied to the proper shipping name that appeared on the freight. The shipper instead provided me with a copy of the shipper's declaration of dangerous goods that should have accompanied the shipment during transportation.
column169: I entered a location code note that all 4 sides of the cargo must be viewed prior to loading to verify no hazmat markings or labels were present based on this issue, despite the shipper's policy that we our drivers are not allowed on the dock during loading.

column168: Circle K reported 200-gallons of Gasoline released from being overfilled impacting a concrete parking area. ERTS dispatched Rock Leaf Water Environmental (RLW) to conduct all onsite clean up operations. Prior to RLW arrival, The City Roads Dept. covered the spill with soil to contain the spill. On July 14, 2022, at 1344 ET, RLW personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 200-gallons of product released to a 40' X 40' concrete lot. There was a culvert that ran off the edge of the parking lot; the drainage culvert leads to soil and a pipe that leads to the sewer. An approximate 10' area of soil between the end of the culvert and the pipe that is pending excavation. RLW collected and containerized (10) 55-gallon Metal Drums of gasoline impacted solids. All waste was transported to RLW facility.

column168: On July 11, 2022, four (4) 125-gallon totes containing CRW9058A were damaged during a vehicular accident/rollover and released approximately two-hundred and seventy (270) gallons of product to the asphalt roadway and soil surface. Baker Hughes Oilfield Operations, Inc. (BH) retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES) to manage the remediation. CES dispatched a crew from Enhanced Environmental and Emergency (E3) to perform the necessary corrective action. E3 personnel transferred remaining product into two (2) 330-gallon totes, then deployed granular absorbents to the impacted asphalt roadway and worked them in with hand tools. Spent absorbents were collected and containerized into six (6) 55-gallon drums. The four (4) empty, damaged totes were deconstructed and containerized into one (1) roll-off box.  On July 14, 2022, E3 personnel returned to the site and excavated the impacted soil area. Impacted soil was containerized into two (2) roll-off boxes for transport and disposal. Following approval of the corrective actions by Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality personnel, E3 demobilized noting no further actions required.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Received report of odor and audible hiss from the top of the car.  Code 3, contractor, assessed the car and determined the car was releasing vapor from the PRD.  The pressure was 250 psi,(PRD set at 280.5) and 25" of outage.  The O-rings were assessed, the larger one appeared deteriorated.  Both were changed and the release stopped.  Car was placed in HZ hold awaiting an OTMA-1
column169: Ensure car is prepared for transportation

column168: SHQX 6076 was reported by citizens to leaking from the top of the car. Inspection by response personnel found 4 of 4 mounting studs on the liquid valve to pressure plate to be less than tool tight. Nuts were tightened stopping the release. Car was decontaminated and moved to the Pierce yard nearby to be set out of train and held for repair and/or OTMA at time of report.
column169: Proper inspection before loading, unloading, and before releasing for shipment.

column168: TILX 161839 was found releasing in the UPRR Winnemucca Yard. The release was due to the liquid line valve being in the open position, plug less than tool tight. The car was secured, decontaminated by Graymar Environmental, and returned to transportation.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Received a call that the car vented product 8-10 feet in the air for 8-10 seconds and then reseated.  The car was inspected by contractors and found to have 150 psi and 21.5" outage with no release.  Car was inspected about 2 hours later and had 270 psi.  The car was reduced to 34" of outage on 7/23/22.
column169: Ensure car is prepared for transportation prior to releasing

column168: RESPONDER USED DECISION TREE, FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS RESPONSE SHEET, WASTE DISPOSAL CHART FOR FULL DMP FACILITY, DECOMTAMINATION CHECKLIST.

UNLOADER DISCOVERED LEAKER HALFWAY THROUGH THE TRAILER LOAD AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR. AS RESPONDER APPROACHED LEAKER, THEY WERE OVERHELMED BY FUMES. USING THE CHAIN OF COMMAND, MANAGER NOTIFIED HAZMAT ONE. HAZMAT ONE DISPATCHED AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER TO CLEAN UP SPILL. THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER CLEANED SPILL BY PLACING INTO TWO 30 GALLON BLUE DRUMS AND LEFT ON SITE.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY DESIGNATED RESPONDER. IT WAS FOUND TO BE A PREVIOUSLY LEAKING HAZMAT THAT HAD NOW DRIED AND WAS LEFT AS A SLIGHTLY DAMP PACKAGE WITH THE CONTENTS STILL INSIDE. THAT THE RESPONDER DONNED FULL PPE PRIOR TO TESTING THE CORROSIVE PH. THE LITTLE AMOUNT OF SPILLED HAZMAT WAS PH BALANCED AND SOLIDIFIED. THE CONTAINER WITH THE LOOSE CAP WAS RESCURED AND THE ENTIRE HAZMAT WAS COLLECTED TO BE PROCESSED IN THE DMP AREA.
PUNCTURED DUE TO DOUBLE STACK

column168: Speed Freight notified ERTS of a cargo release at 23801 S Orchard Access Rd, Boise, ID. It was originally reported that approximately 20 gallons of Sodium Chlorite Solution had been released from a 330-gallon poly tote due to damage during transit. The trailer seal has not been broken, so the amount of damaged totes is unknown. The release impacted a dirt parking lot and the inside of trailer #225723. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor who arrived on site and estimated that approximately 125 gallons released to the trailer floor and adjacent asphalt parking lot. First responders had placed containment to secure the release. The contractor offloaded the leaking IBC and transferred the remaining product into a field supplied IBC. The contractor also conducted addiitonal product transferred from several damaged (but not leaking) IBCs. The contractor crew utilized additional absorbents and a power washer unit to clean the impacted areas. All waste was collected, containerized and staged on site pending waste profiling and final disposal operations.

On July 05, 2022, Landstar contacted ERTS requesting to dispatch a remediation contractor to address a reported “unknown amount of UN2924 released from a 275-gallon IBY tote after being punctured. Following contractor arrival and visual assessment, it was concluded based on this assessment and discussion with a ChampionX representative on site that the driver left the ChampionX facility and at some point, had to apply his brakes very abruptly causing the load to shift forward. The strap holding the tote appeared to have bent the cage surrounding the tote which then punctured the plastic part of the tote causing the release. Driver then turned around and went back to the ChampionX facility where the product leaked onto their parking lot.  A 25' by 15' area of the concrete was impacted and a 6' by 6' area of dirt was impacted. The totes were offloaded and the trailer was wiped down with chemical pads. Allied transferred approximately 210 gallons of product into a new 230 gallon poly tote which ChampionX has deemed as waste. The tote will be staged onsite until Allied can return to pick up the tote for disposal. Absorbents were worked in and recovered and the impacted dirt was collected. Allied generated (3) 85-gallon poly overpacks, two of which contain product impacted absorbent, one containing impacted dirt and respirator cartridges.  Waste is currently pending disposal.

On July 20, 2022, one (1) box containing four (4) 1-gallon bottles of Luperox DDM-9 was punctured by a forklift. As a result, approximately one (1) gallon of product released to the trailer interior and concrete loading dock. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from Enviroserve (ES) to perform the necessary corrective action. ES personnel drummed all damaged freight, then utilized absorbents to remediate the impacted surfaces.

column168: On July 1, 2022, Landstar contacted ERTS requesting to dispatch a remediation contractor to address a reported unknown amount release of DCPD Laminating Resin at a customers location. Upon contractor arrival and following visual assessment, ERTS was informed by the contractor that no damage to the involved drum was observed, and no active leakage was observed, however, the drum of concern was contained within a plastic secondary containment bag that appeared to have approximately ½ gallon of product also contained w/in the bag.  The responding contractor was informed by a representative on site that they thought the leak came from a pinhole sized puncture at the bottom of the drum, but Hepaco personnel did not observe any pinhole. The contents of the drum of concern were successfully transferred into a new drum and affected media was properly cleaned and the contractor generated one 55-gallon drum of waste pending disposal.

column168: RESPONDED TO LEAKER, DETERMINED HAZ MAT. TOOK TO DMP AREA FOR PROCESSING. PROCESSED ENTIRE CONTENTS THROUGH DMP.

AN AUDITED HAZMAT WAS LOADED INTO GRENC ON THE PD1 LOADING DOCK AND WAS DISCOVERED BY THE LOADER WHO THEN NOTIFIED THEIR SUPERVISOR. THE SORT RMP WAS CALLED OVER THE RADIO AND ASKED TO SEND SOMEONE TO CLEAN IT UP. THE RMP SENT THE BEST DESIGNATED RESPONDER TO PD1 TO DO THE JOB. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS WEARING FULL PPE AND HAD A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. UPON ARRIVAL THEY UTILIZED THE REVISED JANUARY 2021 DECICISON TREE AND APPROPIATE RESPONSE SHEET. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE SAFETY MEASURES AND CLEANED THE SPILL AREA THOUROULY, AND NO RESIDUE AND DEBRIS WERE LEFT. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN BROUGHT TO THE PSC TO BE PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP USING THE WASTE DISPOSAL FOR A FULL DMP FACILITY FLOW CHART. PPE AND CONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE ADDED TO DMP BAGS AND THERE WAS A TOTAL OF TWO BAGS. NEXT THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE DECONTAMINATION OF ANY PPE TO GET REUSED. BAG AND TAG PROCEDURE WAS FOLLOWED.

column168: At 0718 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (LSL) about a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift puncture approximately .5 pounds of Securiganth Etch Cleaner C (Hazardous - UN3260) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the dock floor. ERTS dispatched E3 to conduct cleanup. At 0945 ET, E3 personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5 pounds of product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the dock floor. The pallet was broken down and one damaged bag was recovered and containerized. The released material was swept up and placed with the damaged freight into a 55 gallon poly drum. The pallet was then re-stacked and secured for shipment. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Captain Statement: While taxiing onto the runway to line up and wait, the flight attendant called and advised a first row passenger had a cell phone that began to smoke and that she had placed it into the Thermal Containment Bag. We advised ATC, cleared the runway to make contact with SOC and coordinate a return to gate. Maintenance met the plane and the TCB with the cell phone was removed from the plane. While waiting for a replacement TCB, I worked with UA gate staff to make sure the passenger understood the process. Upon completion of the maintenance procedures we departed without any further incident.  Flight Attendant 1 Statement: We were on the runway in line for take off, I was in my jump seat and noticed smoke coming out of a cell phone. Pax was in 1C. Her child had been playing with the phone. the Mom and i noticed the smoke at the same time. I jumped out of my seat grabbed the phone, threw it in the galley, Called the Capitan, and checked for heat on the the phone. I happed so fast I am not sure the order in which this happened. Once I was satisfied that the phone was not hot, I placed the phone and the charger in the red Thermal bag and zipped it. The PAX was upset and insisted that it was the outlet and not the phone, I felt the out let it was cool. I personally saw smoke coming out of the bottom of the phone. We went back to the gate and the CA handled the situation from there. the lady wanted her phone back but the CA would not allow it back on the plane (thank Goodness).  Flight Attendant 2 Statement: Pilot was literally about to take off when FA1 Janey saw smoke in the air. She immediately called Pilot to inform him to not take off then proceeded to get out of jumpseat and assist 1C. She was not sure if it was the charger, phone, or outlet so she put the items in the TCB. Once we went back to the gate, Mesa MTC came on board as well as gate agents. finally, we were told to leave the items behind while the passenger insisted that she wanted her phone back.

column168: Upon arrival at the site, it was determined that a nail from the pallet had punctured the bottom drum head of one 55 gallon poly drum. column169: Recommend the client contact shipper to discuss the quality of pallets being utilized to ship materials.

column168: On July 25, 2022, one (!) 330-gallon tote of Troyguard CM1.5 (UN3265) was punctured by a pallet jack during unloading and released approximately 330 gallons of product to the trailer interior, pavement, and nearby storm drain.  R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to perform the necessary corrective actions. HCE personnel utilized granular absorbents, power washing, and vacuum truck operations to remediate the impacted surfaces. The impacted sump was jetted in both directions with all rinsate collected into the vacuum truck.

column168: At 1236 ET, XPO terminal LEP reported a spill that occurred in El Paso, TX. The spill consisted of boxes containing UN1090 Satwipes which were crushed due to too much freight stacked on top of them, causing an unknown amount of flammable liquid to spill onto the tail of the trailer. Some fumes were reported to be emitting from the boxes as well. ERTS dispatched GrayMar to conduct cleanup. At 1530 ET, contractors arrived onsite and observed a damaged poly bag of wipes. The product did not appear to release to the trailer floor and spill was contained to the package only. The damaged bag was placed into a 15 gallon metal waste drum and the remaining freight on the pallet was stacked for continued transit. Waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: While transporting the tote of Sodium Hydroxide with a forklift to load it into a truck, the forklift traveled  across uneven and rough terrain, which caused to tote to bounce and slide forward on the forks resulting in a fork creating a puncture to the bottom of the tote. The puncture was identified immediately. We then gently placed the tote on its side using the forklift and raised the tote up to a point where the hole was higher than the fluid contained within. We then placed a duck pond beneath the tote and began pumping the fluid into a clean / empty tote. After the fluids were transferred from the damaged tote, we began cleanup of the area.

On July 4, 2022, at 1339 ET, Coca-Cola Ft. Worth reported a release of UN1805 Phosphoric acid impacting the inside of the trailer and under the trailer from a 5-gallon poly pail due to a load shift. ERTS dispatched Lincoln Environmental to preform all onsite clean up operations. On July 4 2022, at 2230 ET Lincoln Environmental arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to a 10-feet (ft.) by 6-inch (in.) area of the trailer floor. Lincoln Environmental placed oil dri on the impacted area. Lincoln Environmental collected and containerized the impacted absorbents into a 20-gallon poly drum. All waste was taken off-site for disposal.

column168: At approximately 10:45 on July 29, 2022 a PCB Release was discovered on an incoming trailer that was staged at dock 2 for offloading. The exact amount of oil released is not able to be determined, but is estimated to be between 1 quart and 1 gallon of oil. The estimate is based on the level of oil remaining in the transformer. The release was from splashing out of the top of the transformer during transportation. The transformer did not have a gasket seal in place and the top was loose with the restraining bolt only lightly tightened, this allowed oil to splash up and over the transformer. PCB oil concentration is 104 PPM. Contacted surfaces and media are: metal ramp and fiberglass wall of the trailer, a pallet jack in the trailer, wood floor planking in the trailer, and water that had accumulated in the loading dock well from a recent rain. Water collected from dock well for disposal as PCB contaminated water, wood form the immediate spill  will be removed from floor of trailer for disposal as PCB debris, metal pallet jack decontaminated with kerosene, wheels of pallet jack replaced, metal flooring and inside wall of trailer decontaminated with kerosene.
column169: To prevent a reoccurence, Veolia is implementing the following safety measures: Verify that all covers are properly secured before attempting to load or transport; Place transformers that contain liquids into secondary containment or drain before shipment; Use metal floor trailers when feasible for shipment of transformers; and Retrain employees as necessary

column168: While unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a drum on a pallet of four that was slightly leaking. column168: AIR PACKAGE BEING SHIPPED FROM THE REPUBLIC OF KOREA TO SLOVAKIA WAS UNABLE TO BE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE IN SLOVAKIA. DURING THE RETURN PROCESS UNDER TRACKING NUMBER W5476456375, PACKAGE CONTENTS WERE VIEWED UNDER X-RAY REVEALING THREE CANS OF AEROSOLS INSIDE. THE PACKAGE HAD PREVIOUSLY FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT FROM ICN TO CGN, THEN CGN TO VIE. THERE WAS A COVERED AIR WAYBILL FROM EMS ON THE OUTER BOX THAT HAD BEEN COVERED WITH A YELLOW STICKER. THERMAL LABEL AND INVOICE DESCRIBES CONTENTS AS SHORTS AND SHOES. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED USING UPS ACCOUNT 6551EX, KOREA POST, 19 DOUM 5RO SEJONG-SI, SEJONG-CITY, KOREA 30114.

column168: SequenceEvent: Unload manager called QA regarding a wet HAZMAT noted while unloading. Inspection revealed a wet, but not otherwise damaged box. Inner contents consisted of four(1) gallon bottles, one of which had a loosely connected lid which allowed contents to escape. The inner contents were not separated by partitions, nor were lids protected. HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin and processed as a damage. DescribePack: The HAZMAT failed as the lid to one of the four bottles was not secure in its connection, hence contents escaped. Lack of internal partitions, as well as padding, over/around lids contribute to the security of closure being compromised. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin, to contain drainage and then processed as a damage.

SequenceEvent: during the overnight sort, the package was brought over to the hazmat cage with signs of internal leakage. Upon inspection 1 of 4 liters of "Sigma-Aldrich Tetrahydrofuran" was found with a loose cap causing the internal leakage. The items were then placed in a hazmat bag and into a drum to await disposition and returned to the shipper. DescribePack: The package failure was a loose cap and internal leakage leaving the bottle almost halfway full. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: the package was immediately opened and inspected, once the loos cap was found we tightly closed it to stop any further internal leakage. It was then placed into a hazmat bag and salvage drum.

SequenceEvent: Package handler discovered the package was wet when he was unloading it from tugger cart and got it to a QA Admin. SequenceEvent: It was in unload area on pallet, brought to QA where we discovered it. DescribePack: Loose cap DurationRel: 10 and MitigateEffect: the release had evaporated its alcohol

SequenceEvent: Package was found with water damage markings. Upon inspection one bottle had a loose cap and was missing fluids. DescribePack: Loose cap DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Cap was screwed on tight. Other bottles were checked and refastened as well.

SequenceEvent: the package was found wet and the box was also ripped up. it was quarantined from the rest of the packages in a hazmat tote until it could be processed by qa DescribePack: an entire corner of the box was ripped on one side and wet on the other. upon inspection of the contents it was found that one of the bottles was leaking. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: making caps are tightly screwed on and adding internal partitions instead of just filling the box with packing peanuts

SequenceEvent: The package was brought back from what appears to be a failed delivery attempt (or was discovered damaged upon delivery), and was discovered leaking powder and upon discovery, was placed in a hazmat bag and bin for further processing and containment. DescribePack: The package was leaking powder and upon further inspection, the pail inside was found to be the cause of the leakage. The lid appears to be in good condition but it isn't preventing the pail from leaking out. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Upon discovery, the pail was placed in a hazmat bag and bin for further processing and containment.

While trying to investigate what happened, the morning QA clerk was told by the Mid shift clerk, that is was not leaking, and all it needed it was a sticker.   During processing, saw that wasn't the case and started to do the damage hazmat processing. DescribePack: Corner of Package was dented inward. All fours cans looked to have been crushed. all handles are bent down. One can has the whole top caved in. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: It was brought over to QA by a package handler at 2:30am, the end of the shift.  and it sat overnight in the cage till 9am where its sat until the Morning QA clerk came in to just find it on his desk. He began to process it and find out why it was left to sit.

SequenceEvent: Driver stated that the package was leaking when retrieving the box from the truck it ripped from the weight of the bottles and softness of the wet box. after box was opened I checked to see if the tops had became loose. only one top was loose. I did not notice much liquid missing from the bottle. DescribePack: Top became loose and the liquid inside spilled out onto the box causing it to get wet and soft and then rip under the weight. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: the caps was retighten to prevent further release of the liquids.

SequenceEvent: PH dropped the package while loading truck. Package was isolated and relocated to hazmat area. DescribePack: after the package was dropped, the glass was broken inside and the content leaked out. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was isolated and relocated to hazmat area.

SequenceEvent: Load manager called QA regarding a malodor emanating from a HAZMAT. On inspection, there was no evidence of damage to the outer, overpack. HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin and processed as a damage. DescribePack: The HAZMAT failed when the seal, designed to secure the lid's closure was compromised. This loss of protection from the seal permitted product to escape. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: HAZMAT was placed in a lined in and processed as a damage.

SequenceEvent: This is an email from the manager that located the item. He is former QA and has held/has certification. There was a Hazmat that spilled on the Silver Belt by Door 603 during the Sunrise sort. It was determined that the Hazmat in question was a Toxic Flammable Liquid known as Pyridine, confirmed via the OP-950 on the package and strong fish like odor associated with the chemical. I called the emergency contact number and got a hold of Ron with Chemtec on proper clean-up process. The process that he instructed us to do was to put some form of absorbent on the spill and keep the area well ventilated, which Noelia and I did immediately following the spill. We removed the trailers from the dock in order to better ventilate the area. Once the spill has been completely absorbed, we are to use rubber gloves and eye protection to scoop up the absorbent and we are to use a plastic shovel to avoid any possibilities of creating sparks. It was advised an Emergency Response Team was not necessary for the situation given we followed the proper procedures immediately following the spill. Report number given to me by the Chemtec Rep was #2022070200060 which he gave to me in order to prove validation that we successfully reported the spill. DescribePack: This chemical is very strong smelling and it was difficult even with PPE to thoroughly inspect each area. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: There was a Hazmat that spilled on the Silver Belt by Door 603 during the Sunrise sort. Dock worker, Brandon Cutler, came into the Supervisors' office at about 1900, to notify Cherilyn Baker, of the hazmat spill. Cutler was going to unload the pallet of hazardous material, when his forklift blade punctured the bottom edge of the drum. Brandon was instructed to get the clean sweep, as B aker got the salvage drum. Baker instructed Cutler to lift the pallet up with the fork lift, so clean sweep could be poured under the pallet, to prevent it from escaping out of the trailer and onto the outside pavement. Cutler lowered the pallet and Alex Hostler came and helped Brandon tip the damag e drum on it's side, to prevent from leaking any further. Hostler and Cutler placed the damage drum on a pallet that they lined with cardboard, to prevent from leaking further onto the dock.

column168: On July 13, 2022, Landstar notified ERTS regarding an unknown hazardous release from cargo on trailer #692943. requesting to dispatch a remediation contractor.  Hepaco arrived onsite and a cargo assessment was done and it was concluded that approximately 50 gallons of product leaked from a pinhole size puncture at the bottom of the involved drum. Of the 50-gallons spilled, approximately 30-gallons released outside the trailer to a 1' by 40' area of the asphalt parking lot. The media affected, trailer components and underlying asphalt, were subsequently addressed and waste generated was containerized and is currently pending disposal.

column168: On July 13, 2022, Landstar notified ERTS of a 5-10 gallon release of UN1760 Step Down “Stripping Solution” that impacted the trailer tire well, trailer floor and the concrete underneath the trailer. ERTS dispatched a remediation contractor to address the reported spill of UN1760.  Grones Environmental arrived onsite,  who following assessment of the involved cargo, determined that 5-gallons of product leaked from a single 5-gallon pail as the result of a crack at the bottom of the pail that was likely caused following a load shift. A Degreaser and oil dri were used appropriately to address the impacted areas. One 55-gallon poly drum was generated and staged at the contractors location until it is disposed of properly.

column168: 1. X-2022080919: Z-CHCPTL3 13A train derailed near Palermo, ND on 07/14/2022.  The derailment  involved lines 23-32 with container FDXU 531152 being involved in the derailment.  Container FDXU 531152 contained 6 totes of Alcohols.  The derailment caused two totes of Alcohols to release due to being crushed.  BNSF contractor repacked the material to prevent further release.  2. X-2022080927: Z-CHCPTL3 13A train derailed near Palermo, ND on 7/14/2022.  The derailment involved lines 23-32 with container RNLU 100590 being involved in the derailment.  RNLU 100590 contained 23 pails of Hypochlorite Solutions.  The derailment caused one 5 gallon pail of Hypochlorite Solution to be released due to being crushed.  BNSF contractor repacked the material to prevent further release.  3. X-2022080928: Z-CHCPTL3 13A train derailed near Palermo, ND on 7/14/2022.  The derailment involved lines 23-32 with container RNLU 100590 being involved in the derailment.  RNLU 100590 contained 5 pails of Isopropanol.  The derailment caused one 5 gallon pail of Isopropanol to be released due to being crushed.  BNSF contractor repacked the material to prevent further release.  4. X-2022080933: Z-CHCPTL3 13A train derailed near Palermo, ND on 7/14/2022.  The derailment involved lines 23-32 with container RNLU 100590 being involved in the derailment.  RNLU 100590 contained 15 boxes containing two 1 gallon bottles of sodium hydroxide in each box.  The derailment caused one box  to be crushed and released two one gallon jugs of sodium hydroxide.  BNSF contractor repacked the material to prevent further release.

The caller stated that the released product was contained to the OS&D dock and had been seeping out over the weekend. The terminal requested a contractor out to inspect the container to ensure procedure to be taken to stop the seeping is adhered to. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct the assessment.  At 0800 ET Hepaco responded and found one Dewar with 25 pounds of pressure still on it. Crew instructed the XPO site to let it bleed off for another 24 hours and when it read 0 PSI it is safe for transport. Hepaco found no other safety risk with the Dewar and advised the same. Crew departed site with no waste generated.

column168: UTLX 204218 was found in the Great Falls yard to be leaking product from the combination housing. Upon inspection, it was noted that the liquid valve was less than tool-tight on the threaded nipple on the pressure plate. The reasoning behind this is that the handle for the valve would not allow for the combination housing cover to close if tool-tightened properly. The valve was removed, the threads re-taped and the valve tool-tightened. The valve handle was removed and zip-tied inside the combination housing.
column169: The shipper must ensure that the valves are tool-tightened and remove the valve handles if necessary to completely close the housing cover.(NAR:282)

column168: On July 24, 2022, Landstar notified ERTS of a cargo release at 700 W. Horton Ave., Colby, KS. It was reported that approximately 1 quart of UN3264, was released from a poly tote due to unknown causes. The release impacted the inside of trailer #768637 and the asphalt parking lot. . No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release.  ERTS dispatched a remediation contractor to address the reported spill of UN3264 f Following contractor arrival, visual assessment of the involved tote resulted in the observation of a small crack at the bottom of the tote. The cause of the crack could not be determined by the contractor, but it was noted that all cargo was secure and strapped down and no damage to the tote cage or tote, other than the small crack at the bottom of the tote, was observed. Media affected was subsequently addressed / neutralized and waste generated is currently pending disposal.

column168: On 07/01/2022, at 1126 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg, WV Yard discovered INVX 26191, a loaded  tank car of Hexamethylenediamine, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and West Virginia DEP were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0701-00331). Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a significantly deteriorated manway nozzle gasket that resulted in the release of lading. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Thomas Moon of INV Nylon Chemicals, phone 316-252-7642. Contractor personnel removed the defective gasket and replaced in kind and secure the manway per 49 CFR 173.31, and cleaned all spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 209 NARRI: 80

On 07/04/2022, at 0453 hours, personnel in the CSXT Walbridge, OH Yard observed and odor from GATX 66084, a loaded tank car of Isobutylene. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0704-00017). Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an active vapor release from the thermometer well. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Art Board, IV, phone 713-857-0471. Because the release occurred through the thermometer well, a Midland Emergency Response Kit was installed and the tank car was monitored daily in order to coordinate a receiving car. GATX 66084 contents were successfully transferred on 7/14/2022, and cleaned and purged on 7/15/2022, thus securing the release. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: NARRI:525

On 07/27/2022, at 1925 hours, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Terminal discovered TILX 111596, a loaded  tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0803-00215). Joseph Taylor and Ryan Godsey, CSX Managers of Hazardous Materials were dispatched to the scene and discovered the liquid eduction line primary closure flange was improperly secured - 1 of 4 securement studs were observed with one missing securement nut. Additionally, it was determined a contributing factor to the release of lading was due to pressure in the outage / vapor space that resulted in material elevating through the liquid eduction line and past the improperly secured closure. The CSX Managers relieved the vapor pressure by opening the vapor valve and the release was immediately stopped, to which the primary closure was then secured.  Enviroserve, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and assisted with the cleanup of all spilled material to the ground, and decontaminated all exterior surfaces of the car from residue lading. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Doug Nestler of Univar Solutions, phone (408) 221-4964. Because of the significance of the release, an approved Mobile Repair Unit will replace all studs on the liquid line primary closure before the car is released to continue in transportation. This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 243  NARRI: 100

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: On 7/23/2022 at 11:48 AM, Kansas City Southern Railway's(KCS) Environmental& Hazmat Department became aware that loaded Ethyl Mercaptan tank car UTLX 900604 was emanatlng an odor at the Car Shop located in the KCS Shreveport rail yard. The Car Shop was instructed to remove the car for them shop and to spot the car so responders could investigate the odor. A railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to investigate and mitigate the release. Upon arrival, responders found no visible signs of release after opening the protective housing. With the use of a Multi-Rae 4.Gas PID air monitor, the leak was detected at the sample valve end plug. Responders found the sample valve and the sample valve end plug were both less than tool tight. With the use of a wrench, the the sample valve and the sample valve end plug were rendered tool tight. After approximately a 20-minute wait time, the closures were checked again with the Multi-Rae meter to assure that the leak was secured. The Multi-Rae meter reading was non-detect. In addition, olfactory senses could not detect an odor. Estimated release was one quart. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: several different levels. column168: During the initial inspection, HEPACO crew members determined approximately 3 gallons of styrene was released onto Florence Mall' s parking lot. The impacted area was approximately 2 feet In length and 3 feet in width. HEPACO crew members initiated work operations by dispersing absorbents onto the affected area. The absorbents were then swept up leaving a visible stain on the asphalt. After completion of the aforementioned activity, HEPACO crew supervisor, Richard Legette, climbed atop the tanker to inspect the dome lid which was the source of the styrene spill. After inspection, it was determined that the dome lid rubber gasket was missing which resulted in the spill. A replacement gasket was given to Mr. Legette by the driver of the tanker and Installed utilizing a non-sparking rubber mallet. The dome lid was then bolted and secured immediately after installation concluded. THe The generated waste, debris, and PPE was placed into one(1) 55-gallon poly drum. Transportation and disposal of the waste was completed under non-hazardous waste manifest No.: 2243.020099. The team members demobilized and returned to the office where equipment was cleaned, restocked, and prepared for future service.

column168: This package was discovered to be leaking during the sort. Upon inspection of the contents it appeared to be a re-used box with one 1 gallon paint can inside wrapped in plastic. The can leaked from the lid. The inner paint can had Globally Harmonized System (GHS) labels of flammable, exclamation point and health hazard as well as an environmentally hazard mark. The product is a BASF 285-02 low VOC transparent sealer. The manufacturer’s Safety Data Sheet (SDS) lists a flash point of minus 18 degrees Celsius. Section 14 of the SDS lists the identification/classification as UN 1263, Paint, 3, Packing Group II for the IATA/ICAO air transport regulations. As the shipper had not offered the shipment with any DG markings, labels nor a shipper’s declaration, it is undeclared/hidden dangerous goods. The FAA was notified via email and photos sent. The package was held pending FAA investigation until they released it.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred, During inspection prior to transport, driver discovered leak inside of the trailer. Trailer was isolated and Environmental Restoration LLC (ERLLC) was dispatched to inspect the Ieaking tote. ERLLC arrived and inspected the site. ERLLC determined that the tote had a small puncture and liquid was sloshing during transport resulting in the release. The trailer was secured pending product transfer the following day. On July 8 ERLLC returned to the site. ERLLC pumped the product from the Ieaking site into a new tote for delivery. ERLLC deployed absorbent material to recover the free liquid from the trailer floor. The waste was left on site for disposal by N&M Transfer.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, N&M Transfer will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. Tri-State Motor Transit driver arrived to pick up trailer and attach to tractor. Upon arrival, a leak was detected coming from nose of trailer, while trailer was parked in lot. Absorbent material was applied to contain the free product and secure site, prior to contractor arrival. Clean Harbors Environmental Services was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, Clean Harbors secured the area and monitored trailer until field crew arrived. Clean Harbors proceeded to locate the Ieaking drum inside the trailer, which was one 55-gallon poly overpack, which was discovered with a pinhole leak. Approximately 4 gallons of free product released to trailer floor and asphalt beneath trailer. Clean Harbors proceeded to overpack the leaking drum, used absorbents to clean trailer floor, and recovered all spent absorbent utilized on parking lot, which were placed with Ieaking drum inside overpack. Drum was left on trailer to continue on to destination, as waste. There were no injuries or exposures reported. Attached copy of waste manifest 002036160

column168: On July 30, 2022, ERTS was contacted by Landstar personnel in Mebane, North Carolina requesting facilitation of the cleanup of a trailer that was reported to be transporting empty drums. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed the release of approximately 5 gallons of Sipomer Iboma HP (Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, n.o.s. (Isobornyl Methacrylate), UN3082) to a 2’ by 10’ area of the trailer floor.  The contractors then utilized clay absorbent material to address residual product observed. The damaged 55-gallon drums were placed into (2) 85-gallon metal drum overpacks. The spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The waste drums were then transported by the contractor to Clean Management Environmental Group in Walterboro, South Carolina for proper disposal.

column168: While conducting post-trip inspection, the driver noticed drops of dried dark material on the skirts of the trailer carrying hazardous waste. The material was no longer dripping at the time of discovery and the driver concluded that immediate action was not required.  The driver contacted emergency response for trailer investigation and clean up. Emergency response arrived and entered the trailer. A long stain was discovered along the floor of the trailer. The stain appeared to have been released from a 55-gallon drum with stains around the bung, but no evidence of an active leak was discovered. The suspected drum was placed in a salvage drum and the stain on the trailer floor was cleaned to the best of their ability.  Upon inspection and investigation, it was determined that the likely root cause of this release was due to not properly checking the closure of the bung.

column168: At or about 11:45am on 07/30/2022, the cargo tank vehicle containing 5000 gallons of product experienced a fire on the rear axles of the tank. The driver stopped in the emergency lane and attempted to extinguish the fire via portable on-board fire extinguisher. The driver was not able to extinguish the fire and then disconnected the power unit from the trailer. The fire department arrived and extinguished the fire. The fire had melted all of the tires and the gaskets on discharge valving system causing the product in the tanker to begin to leak at a rate of about 3-4 gallons a minute.   Florida Highway Patrol had arrived and closed the section of I-75S near ext 154 to traffic.  The fire department conducted immediate containment measures; brought in truck loads of dirt to construct a berm to contain the run off. The company mobilized their emergency response contractors and other company personnel to assist. A company truck arrived to trans-load the product into another vehicle while contractors continued containment efforts. Once the product was transferred to another tanker and the leak had stopped, a towing service removed the tanker from the highway and traffic resumed.  A clean up plan was agreed upon with the Florida Department of Environmental Protection, the emergency response contractor and company leadership.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ROSS FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER AND ONE DRUM OF FOUR DRUMS ON A WOODEN PALLET APPEARED TO HAVE A DAMAGE WOODEN PALLET UNDER THEM. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR CAUGHT/PUNCTURED THE DRUM WITH A FORKLIFT FORK WHILE TRYING TO GET UNDER THE WOODEN PALLET AND A LEAK OCCURRED. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR BACKED OUT OF THE TRAILER REMOVING ALL IGNITION SOURCES AND CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK ON PROPER HM CLEANUP. THE DOCK EMPLOYEE WAS DIRECTED TO HAVE THE TRAILER MOVED AWAY FROM THE BUILDING ON PAVEMENT AND AWAY FROM ANY WATER DRAINS AND WATER SOURCES. THE TRAILER REAR DOOR WAS OPENED TO VENTILATE TO THE OUTSIDE, DUE TO THE STRONG SMELL AND CONTAINED THE SPILL BY PLACING SPEEDY DRY PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR TO ABSORB THE ACCESS PRODUCT THAT HAD SPREAD ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. LATER IN THE DAY THE ASST. SUPERVISOR WITH HELP FROM A DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GO INTO THE VENTILATED TRAILER TO UPRIGHT THE DRUM WITH EXCESS PRODUCT STILL IN THE DRUM AND PLACE THE BLUE PLASTIC 55 GALLON DRUM INTO A 95 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. ALL THE CLEANUP SUPPLIES USED WERE PLACED ALSO IN A LARGE YELLOW 95 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. PRODUCT IS BEING VENTILATED AS IT IS BEING PREPARED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: On 7-5-22 at 0700 personnel in the CSXT Goulding Yard discovered MULX135678, a residue tank car of Dimethylamine, Anhydrous leaking from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and Polychemie Inc were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2022070500053). E3 Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that vapors were being released from both liquid line valves and vapor line valves.  All three valves were not in the closed position and all three secondary closure plugs were found to be less than tool tight. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Stacy Hamlin at 912-432-5220. Contractor personnel closed all the valves and properly tool tightened all three secondary closure plugs. The leak was secured and the car will require an OTMA 1 to be sent to home shop for inspection of valves and closures. This incident did require a special switching move.  Tank car had to be placed into a shop track until OTMA 1 is approved for movement to home shop.

column168: Frontier Justice shipped a cardboard gaylord on a pallet with labels for Exxon Mobil oil. The BOL read only brass in the description. The gaylord actually contained spent and live ammunition with loose gunpowder. When offloading with a forklift, the gaylord exploded. It eventually lead to the death of the forklift driver two days later. A second gaylord was removed from the trailer and a 5 gallon bucket worth of powder was found.
column169: Spent brass is rarely cleaned well enough to pose no risk in shipping. Most firing ranges sweep up the shells and powder together before packaging for shipment. It is impossible to know the risks posed to the carrier.

column168: During taxi out for take-off, a Flight Attendant smelled an electrical odor, and immediately the passenger in 16D blurted out that a man's battery is burning behind him. The Flight Attendant immediately looked at the passenger in 17E and he gives the Flight Attendant his iced tea bottle(with liquid still inside) and the battery in it. The bottle felt warm and the passenger said that his battery was the old model and that s why it probably sparked. He said everything was fine and he put it in his ice tea drink with the lid closed. The number 2 Flight Attendant, came up to the number 4 Flight Attendant and told her that she had to let the Captain know in case he wanted to throw out the battery or have the man investigated. We called the Captain, and he said that we are going back to the gate to get rid of this battery. We had a Gate Agent come on board and talk to the man and found that he had more batteries in his bag. We asked if he could just leave the batteries so he could still fly with us, and he refused to do so. The customer and his lithium ion batteries were removed and the flight re-departed. Spoke with the customer on the phone. He had 4 lithium ion battery cells, 2 in his e-cigarette and 2 spares. One of the spares must have arced with the zipper in his carry-on bag causing a short. He had a carryin case but it had broken so he did not have it to protect the batteries from short circuit.
column169: lithium ion batteries in carry-on baggage. Better education of the public about the dangers of lithium ion batteries.

column168: WHAT: Three Unit Personal Injury Traffic Crash  WHERE: IL-108 at Standard City Road, Macoupin  WHEN: July 12, 2022 at approximately 7:56 AM.  VEHICLE: Unit 2- 2021 White Peterbuilt 2 Axle Tanker Truck  DRIVE: Unit 2- Ronald Hallbauer, 60-year-old male of Carlinville, IL (Transported to a local area hospital with injuries)  PRELIMINARY: Unit 1, a Truck-Tractor Semi-Trailer combination, was traveling eastbound on IL Route 108 just west of Standard City Rd. Unit 2, a Pickup, was in front of Unit 1. Unit 3, a Straight Truck with Propane Tank, was directly in front of Unit 2. Unit 3 slowed while approaching the intersection at Standard City Rd, to make a left turn. Unit 2 slowed with Unit 3, also to make a left turn. As Unit 2 and Unit 3 slowed, Unit 1 did not see them slow down. Unit 1 saw Unit 2 slowed and was unable to avoid Unit 2. Unit 1 heavily applied brakes, striking Unit 2's rear with Unit 1's front. Propane leak resulted.

column168: On 07/12/2022 LARS received notification from Hub personnel that unit JBHU 305907 (Hazmat Load) was observed leaking after the unit was deramped from the railcar at the Los Angeles Intermodal Facility. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed inside of the containment pit pending a cargo inspection. Environmental contractor (United Pumping) was dispatched to perform a cargo inspection and to remediate the leaking product along with the affected areas. Interior inspection revealed mixed palletized freight along with 330 gallon totes varying in sizes and weights throughout the entire unit. A 330 gallon tote at the nose of the unit containing "Fabra Kleen Terminator" (Sodium Hydroxide Solution a corrosive liquid) was found to be leaking due to failed packaging. The contractor was able to remediate the spill and affected areas, the product was transferred in to a new tote. The shipment was reloaded / secured with seal 27670381, this shipment has been released for out   gate at the drivers discretion.
column169: Inspection of containers prior, during and after loading to ensure any damage is identified prior to offering.

column168: On 2022   07   14 this hazmat shipment was observed leaking after deramp at the Stockton Intermodal Facility. On your behalf a contractor was dispatched to inspect and remediate leaking condition. Interior inspection of the unit revealed a shipment of mixed cargo throughout, double stacked with only a cargo strap for securement. At the rear of the load, one pallet had fallen over causing damage to cargo underneath. Closer inspection revealed a pallet containing 5 gallon buckets of "Hentzen Clear Expoxy Hybrid" which was damaged and leaking. It is estimated that approximately 1 quart of epoxy leaked from 2 buckets (no signs of actual ground contamination). Damaged cargo was overpacked into 55 gallon drums. Trailer was cleaned and waste products were also overpacked into drums. Cargo was reloaded to trailer with drums placed at the rear of the load for ABF safe handling.
column169: Proper securement of loads and items stacked to ensure minimal movement during transportation.
